{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When pathogens enter your body, they trigger an alarm. Watch as immune sensors detect these invaders and sound the alert, like a security system detecting intruders.",
      "title": "Pathogen Invasion"
    },
    {
      "text": "Neutrophils and macrophages rush to the scene. They're like the SWAT team, engulfing and devouring pathogens. Notice how they quickly contain the threat.",
      "title": "First Responders Arrive"
    },
    {
      "text": "B cells produce antibodies that fit the pathogen like a lock and key. See how these molecular handcuffs mark the invaders for destruction, making them easier targets.",
      "title": "Antibody Lockdown"
    },
    {
      "text": "T cells inspect infected cells and coordinate the attack. Some directly kill infected cells while others call in reinforcements. It's like a military command center directing operations.",
      "title": "T Cells Activate"
    },
    {
      "text": "After the battle, memory cells remain. They're like veterans who remember past enemies, staying on high alert for future invasions. This creates long-term immunity.",
      "title": "Memory Cells Form"
    },
    {
      "text": "The combined efforts of antibodies, T cells, and other immune cells clear the infection. Watch as your body restores balance and returns to normal function.",
      "title": "Pathogen Elimination"
    },
    {
      "text": "Memory cells stay ready for years, sometimes a lifetime. If the same pathogen returns, they spring into action, mounting a faster, stronger response than before.",
      "title": "Immune Memory Persists"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Watch as the DNA double helix unwinds at the gene to be transcribed. One strand will serve as the template for RNA synthesis.",
      "title": "DNA Unwinds"
    },
    {
      "text": "RNA polymerase binds to the promoter region on the DNA. This is like finding the correct starting line on a DNA 'track' where transcription begins.",
      "title": "RNA Polymerase Arrives"
    },
    {
      "text": "The RNA polymerase begins to move along the DNA template strand, reading its bases. The process has started, and RNA synthesis is underway.",
      "title": "Transcription Starts"
    },
    {
      "text": "As RNA polymerase moves, it adds complementary RNA nucleotides to the growing RNA chain. A pairs with U, T pairs with A, C pairs with G, and G pairs with C.",
      "title": "RNA Chain Grows"
    },
    {
      "text": "Behind the RNA polymerase, the DNA strands rewind into their double helix structure. The newly synthesized RNA strand is released.",
      "title": "DNA Rewinds"
    },
    {
      "text": "When RNA polymerase reaches a terminator sequence, it releases the newly formed RNA transcript and detaches from the DNA. The process is complete.",
      "title": "Transcription Ends"
    },
    {
      "text": "In eukaryotes, the RNA transcript undergoes processing — modifications like splicing, capping, and tailing before it becomes mature mRNA ready for translation.",
      "title": "RNA Processing"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When you type a URL and hit enter, your browser creates an HTTP request. Think of it like writing a letter — you're specifying the destination and what you want.",
      "title": "You Enter a URL"
    },
    {
      "text": "The browser asks DNS (like a phone book) to translate the domain name into an IP address. This is where your request will be sent.",
      "title": "DNS Resolves the Address"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your browser establishes a TCP connection to the server. It's like creating a dedicated phone line for your request.",
      "title": "TCP Connection Opens"
    },
    {
      "text": "The HTTP request travels through the TCP connection to the server. It includes your method (GET, POST, etc.), headers (metadata), and sometimes body data.",
      "title": "Request is Sent"
    },
    {
      "text": "The server receives your request, understands what you want (thanks to the HTTP method), and processes it. This might involve database queries or other operations.",
      "title": "Server Processes Request"
    },
    {
      "text": "The server creates an HTTP response containing status codes (200, 404, etc.), headers (more metadata), and the requested data (if successful).",
      "title": "Response is Generated"
    },
    {
      "text": "The HTTP response travels back through the TCP connection to your browser. It's like receiving a letter in response to the one you sent.",
      "title": "Response Travels Back"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your browser receives the response and acts on it. If it's HTML, it renders the page. If it's data, it might be handled by JavaScript code.",
      "title": "Browser Renders the Response"
    },
    {
      "text": "Once the response is fully received, the TCP connection typically closes. The transaction is complete, like hanging up after a phone call.",
      "title": "Connection Closes"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "As your program runs, objects get created on the heap. Think of it like a warehouse where boxes (objects) get stored as needed.",
      "title": "Memory Allocation Happens"
    },
    {
      "text": "When your code uses these objects, references to them are maintained. As long as something references a box, it stays in the warehouse.",
      "title": "References Keep Objects Alive"
    },
    {
      "text": "The garbage collector identifies root objects — global variables, stack variables, and CPU registers. These are like the warehouse's inventory tracking system.",
      "title": "GC Roots Are Established"
    },
    {
      "text": "The GC starts from roots and traces all reachable objects. It's like following inventory lists to find every box that's still in use.",
      "title": "Reachability Check Begins"
    },
    {
      "text": "Objects that aren't reachable from roots are marked as garbage. These are boxes with no inventory records — they're considered unused.",
      "title": "Unreachable Objects Identified"
    },
    {
      "text": "The GC reclaims memory from unreachable objects. It's like clearing out unused boxes from the warehouse to free up space.",
      "title": "Memory Reclamation Occurs"
    },
    {
      "text": "To prevent fragmentation, the GC might compact the heap. This is like rearranging remaining boxes so they occupy contiguous space.",
      "title": "Heap Compaction May Follow"
    },
    {
      "text": "The garbage collection cycle finishes, and your program continues running with more available memory. The warehouse is tidy and ready for new boxes.",
      "title": "Cycle Completed"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A luz solar atinge os fotossistemas nas membranas dos tilacoides, excitando os elétrons da clorofila. É como quando você liga um interruptor e a energia começa a fluir.",
      "title": "Luz Aciona Fotossistemas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Os elétrons excitados são transferidos para uma cadeia de transporte de elétrons, como uma corrente elétrica fluindo por um circuito.",
      "title": "Elétrons em Movimento"
    },
    {
      "text": "À medida que os elétrons se movem pela cadeia, eles impulsionam o bombeamento de prótons para dentro do tilacoide, criando um gradiente de concentração.",
      "title": "Protons se Acumulam"
    },
    {
      "text": "O gradiente de prótons faz com que eles fluam de volta pelo complexo ATP sintase, que usa essa energia para produzir ATP a partir de ADP e fosfato.",
      "title": "ATP Sintase em Ação"
    },
    {
      "text": "Os elétrons que passaram pela cadeia de transporte finalmente reduzem NADP+ a NADPH, armazenando energia química para o ciclo de Calvin.",
      "title": "Elétrons Reduzem NADP+"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com ATP e NADPH produzidos, a fase clara da fotossíntese está completa. Esses produtos energéticos serão usados na fase escura para fixar carbono.",
      "title": "Energia Química Gerada"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagina un mercado como una subasta gigante. Los compradores llegan con diferentes precios máximos que están dispuestos a pagar por un producto. Algunos están dispuestos a pagar más, otros menos.",
      "title": "Los Compradores Entran al Mercado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mientras tanto, los vendedores tienen sus propios precios mínimos para vender. Estos precios reflejan sus costos de producción y ganancias esperadas. Algunos pueden vender más barato, otros más caro.",
      "title": "Los Vendedores Establecen sus Precios"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando compradores y vendedores interactúan, ocurre algo mágico. Los compradores buscan los mejores precios y los vendedores compiten por vender. Esto crea una danza de ofertas y demandas.",
      "title": "Las Interacciones Comienzan"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si hay más compradores que vendedores, los precios tienden a subir. Los vendedores se dan cuenta de que pueden cobrar más y los compradores están dispuestos a pagar más para obtener el producto.",
      "title": "El Precio se Ajusta"
    },
    {
      "text": "A medida que los precios suben o bajan, el mercado se mueve hacia un punto de equilibrio. Aquí, la cantidad que los compradores quieren comprar iguala la cantidad que los vendedores quieren vender.",
      "title": "El Equilibrio se Alcanza"
    },
    {
      "text": "En este punto de equilibrio, el mercado se estabiliza. No hay presión para que los precios suban o bajen drásticamente porque la oferta y la demanda están en armonía.",
      "title": "El Mercado se Estabiliza"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pero el mercado no se queda quieto. Cambios en la oferta o demanda pueden mover el equilibrio. Por ejemplo, una nueva tecnología puede reducir costos y aumentar la oferta, bajando los precios.",
      "title": "Cambios en el Mercado"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A stray neutron collides with a U-235 nucleus. This is the spark that sets off the chain reaction, like a single domino falling.",
      "title": "Neutron Collision"
    },
    {
      "text": "The U-235 nucleus absorbs the neutron and becomes unstable. It splits into smaller nuclei, releasing more neutrons and energy.",
      "title": "Fission Occurs"
    },
    {
      "text": "The fission releases 2-3 new neutrons, which fly out in different directions. These neutrons are like messengers carrying the reaction to other nuclei.",
      "title": "Neutrons Released"
    },
    {
      "text": "If these new neutrons hit other U-235 nuclei, they cause more fission events. Each event releases more neutrons, creating a cascade effect.",
      "title": "Chain Reaction Begins"
    },
    {
      "text": "As more nuclei split, the reaction spreads through the fissile material. The rate of fission accelerates if enough neutrons hit other nuclei.",
      "title": "Reaction Propagates"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the reaction becomes self-sustaining, critical mass is reached. The material is now producing neutrons faster than they're lost.",
      "title": "Critical Mass Achieved"
    },
    {
      "text": "In reactors, control rods absorb excess neutrons to regulate the reaction. Without control, the chain reaction accelerates until the material is consumed or dispersed.",
      "title": "Control or Runaway"
    },
    {
      "text": "As fission continues, energy is released according to E=mc². This energy heats the surrounding material, which can be used to generate power or cause destruction.",
      "title": "Energy Release"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Watch as the magnet moves near the coil. The magnetic field through the coil changes, like water flowing into or out of a container.",
      "title": "Magnetic Field Changes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Notice how the changing magnetic field alters the flux through the coil. It's like changing the amount of water in the container - the level rises or falls.",
      "title": "Flux Through Coil"
    },
    {
      "text": "As the flux changes, an electromotive force (EMF) is induced in the coil. Think of it like a pump creating pressure in a water pipe - voltage is building up.",
      "title": "EMF Induced"
    },
    {
      "text": "The induced EMF drives current through the circuit. See how the changing magnetic field has created an electric current without any battery.",
      "title": "Current Flows"
    },
    {
      "text": "The faster the magnet moves, the greater the rate of change of flux. Notice how this increases the induced EMF and current - like turning up the pump's pressure.",
      "title": "Faraday's Law in Action"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the magnet reverses direction, the change in flux reverses. Watch how this changes the direction of induced current - like reversing the pump's flow.",
      "title": "Direction Matters"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the magnet stops moving, the flux stops changing. See how the induced current disappears - like the pump stopping.",
      "title": "No Change, No Current"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "O substrato se aproxima e se liga ao sítio ativo da enzima. Imagine uma chave entrando na fechadura — a forma complementar permite uma ligação precisa.",
      "title": "Substrato se Liga"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com o substrato ligado, forma-se o complexo enzima-substrato. Este complexo é como um estado temporário onde tudo está pronto para a reação acontecer.",
      "title": "Complexo se Forma"
    },
    {
      "text": "A enzima aplica tensão nas ligações do substrato e estabiliza o estado de transição. É como esticar uma mola — acumula energia para a transformação.",
      "title": "Tensão e Estabilização"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com a barreira de energia reduzida, a reação química ocorre. O substrato se transforma em produto(s) enquanto ainda ligado à enzima.",
      "title": "Reação Acontece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Os produtos da reação são liberados do sítio ativo. A enzima agora está livre para catalisar outra reação — seu trabalho está feito.",
      "title": "Produto é Liberado"
    },
    {
      "text": "A enzima retorna à sua configuração original, pronta para receber outro substrato. O ciclo pode se repetir milhões de vezes.",
      "title": "Enzima Reiniciada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fatores como temperatura, pH e concentração de substrato afetam a atividade enzimática. É como ajustar as condições ideais para uma reação ocorrer.",
      "title": "Fatores que Influenciam"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "La corriente eléctrica entra en la celda electrolítica a través del ánodo (positivo). Los electrones fluyen desde la fuente de poder hacia el ánodo.",
      "title": "Corriente Eléctrica Fluye"
    },
    {
      "text": "En el ánodo, los iones negativos (aniones) pierden electrones debido a la corriente eléctrica. Este proceso se llama oxidación.",
      "title": "Oxidación en el Ánodo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los electrones que entraron por el ánodo viajan a través del circuito externo hasta el cátodo (negativo). Aquí, los iones positivos (cationes) ganan estos electrones, reduciéndose.",
      "title": "Reducción en el Cátodo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mientras tanto, en la solución, los cationes se mueven hacia el cátodo y los aniones hacia el ánodo. Este movimiento mantiene la neutralidad eléctrica en la solución.",
      "title": "Movimiento de Iones"
    },
    {
      "text": "La combinación de oxidación en el ánodo y reducción en el cátodo fuerza reacciones químicas no espontáneas. Se producen sustancias nuevas en ambos electrodos.",
      "title": "Reacciones Químicas Ocurren"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los productos de estas reacciones se recogen en los electrodos. Pueden ser gases (como H₂ o O₂), metales depositados o otras sustancias, dependiendo del electrolito.",
      "title": "Productos de la Electrólisis"
    },
    {
      "text": "La corriente eléctrica continua mantiene el proceso. La electrólisis sigue ocurriendo mientras haya suministro de corriente y los reactivos necesarios en la solución.",
      "title": "Proceso Completo"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "The central bank changes its policy rate, like adjusting a thermostat for the economy. A lower rate stimulates growth; a higher rate cools it down.",
      "title": "Central Bank Acts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Commercial banks adjust their interest rates in response to the policy rate change. Lower rates make borrowing cheaper for consumers and businesses.",
      "title": "Commercial Banks Respond"
    },
    {
      "text": "With lower interest rates, banks lend more. Consumers borrow for homes and cars. Businesses invest in expansion and new projects.",
      "title": "Credit Becomes Cheaper"
    },
    {
      "text": "Through open market operations, the central bank injects money into the economy by buying government bonds. This increases bank reserves.",
      "title": "Money Supply Increases"
    },
    {
      "text": "By lowering reserve requirements, banks can lend a larger portion of their deposits. This amplifies the effect of the initial rate cut.",
      "title": "Reserve Requirements Shift"
    },
    {
      "text": "As credit flows into the economy, spending and investment rise. This boosts economic activity, potentially increasing inflation.",
      "title": "Economic Activity Picks Up"
    },
    {
      "text": "With more money chasing goods and services, businesses may raise prices. The central bank must balance growth against inflation risks.",
      "title": "Inflation Pressure Builds"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the economy overheats, the central bank can raise rates, increase reserve requirements, or sell bonds to slow things down.",
      "title": "The Cycle Reverses"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "The compilation journey begins when you feed your source code into the compiler. Think of it like submitting a recipe to a master chef — the ingredients are your code, and the kitchen is the compiler.",
      "title": "Source Code Enters"
    },
    {
      "text": "The lexer chops your code into tokens — keywords, identifiers, operators, and literals. It's like separating ingredients for your recipe into individual bowls.",
      "title": "Lexer Breaks It Down"
    },
    {
      "text": "The parser organizes these tokens into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST). Imagine constructing a hierarchical recipe diagram — main steps, sub-steps, and ingredients nested properly.",
      "title": "Parser Builds Structure"
    },
    {
      "text": "The compiler checks your code's meaning through semantic analysis. It's like verifying that your recipe makes sense — ingredients exist, steps are valid, and quantities match expectations.",
      "title": "Semantic Analysis"
    },
    {
      "text": "The compiler generates Intermediate Representation (IR) from the AST. Think of it as creating a standardized cooking procedure that any kitchen can follow, regardless of their specific tools.",
      "title": "Intermediate Representation Created"
    },
    {
      "text": "The compiler optimizes the IR. It's like refining your recipe for efficiency — combining steps, eliminating unnecessary actions, and improving the overall workflow.",
      "title": "Optimization Phase"
    },
    {
      "text": "The compiler translates optimized IR into machine code. Imagine the master chef finally preparing your dish using the kitchen's specific equipment and ingredients.",
      "title": "Code Generation"
    },
    {
      "text": "The final machine code is assembled into an executable file. It's like packaging your perfectly cooked dish for serving — ready to run on the target machine.",
      "title": "Output Assembly"
    },
    {
      "text": "If anything goes wrong during these steps — syntax errors, type mismatches, or optimization issues — the compiler reports them. It's like the kitchen staff catching a problem in your recipe before serving.",
      "title": "When Errors Occur"
    }
  ]
}
